\subsection{Corner Diffraction}\label{LR_Corner_Diff}\index{Corner!diffraction}
The problems of diffraction by a plane angular sector and that by a cone are canonical problems for corner diffraction. In \cite{Radlow_Note_diffraction_corner}, \cite{R_Satterwhite_quarter_plane}, \cite{Satterwhite_EM_diff_perfectly_conducting_plane} exact analytic solutions to the problem of diffraction by a plane sector are presented. A dyadic Green\rq s function for the problem of scattering from a perfectly conducting plane angular sector was first derived by Satterwhite from the exact solution in \cite{Satterwhite_Ph_thesis} using the method of separation of variables in spheroconal coordinates. This dyadic function is in a complicated nonclosed form expression involving spherical Bessel and Lame’ functions and has very poor convergence properties when both source and field points are far from the comer \cite{R_Satterwhite_quarter_plane}. Therefore, it is not a sufficiently practical solution for high frequency comer diffraction calculations. Thorkild B. Hansen obtained a numerical solution to the electric field integral to the electrical-field integral equation for the problem of scattering of an incident plane wave \cite{Hansen_Corner_diff_coeff_quarter_plane}, \cite{Hansen_Diff_plane_angular_sector_new_derivation}, \cite{Hansen_field_scattered_plane_angular_sector}. Analytical expressions for the edge wave currents for forward direction incidence were constructed from the numerical results. These expressions were valid for limited range of incidence and also not applicable to small angle corners. 

A recent paper \cite{Budaev_Diffraction_plane_wave_DN_boundary_condition} suggests an approach, based on the random walk method, to solve the problem of diffraction by a semi-infinite sector with Dirichlet or Neuman boundary conditions. Unfortunately this paper does not provide asymptotic expansions of the exact solution nor does it provide expressions for diffraction coefficients \cite{Volski_Heuristic_Diffraction_Coefficient_Dielectric_Slab}.

The basic postulate of GTD and its variants the UAT and UTD is that diffraction is a local phenomenon and therefore depends only on the local geometry of the problem in hand. For the problem of edge diffraction it therefore considers the local geometry the same as that of the canonical problem of diffraction by a half-plane. The edge is therefore assumed to extend to infinity on both sides. However, all physical edges are finite and must stop at a corner of a plane. Burnside, Wang, and Pelton \cite{Burnside_airborne_antennas} developed heuristically a comer diffraction coefficient to account for the termination of an edge in a finite perfectly conducting object. This coefficient was based on an asymptotic evaluation of the radiation integral for the equivalent currents that would exist in the absence of the comer. The asymptotic result was then empirically modified to yield their comer diffraction term.


In \cite{Burnside_tip_diffraction} the comer diffraction formulation of \cite{Burnside_airborne_antennas} is modified for the case of a dielectric comer. The modification is an extension of the work of Burnside and Burgener \cite{Burnside_HF_scattering_thin_lossless_dielectric_slab} on the two-dimensional dielectric slab, and that of DeWitt \cite{DeWitt_Phd_Thesis_wedge_absorber} on the twodimensional dielectric wedge. A high-frequency dielectric comer diffraction solution has been developed in \cite{Burnside_tip_diffraction}.

In summary, no explicitly exact solution or sufficiently practical solution to the general problem of corner diffraction exists nor do the asymptotic forms of these solutions. The heuristic corner diffraction coefficient of Burnside $et~al.$ \cite{Burnside_tip_diffraction} though practically useful, is limited by its first order nature and failure to provide higher order slope diffraction.
